Identifying Customer Segments using Expectation Maximization Clustering

Oracle Machine Learning supports clustering using several algorithms: k-Means, O-Cluster, and Expectation Maximization. paragraphs.title: Prepare data set for model building from customer demographic data in proxy object CUST_DF
paragraphs.text:
%r

ore.sync(query = c("SUPPLEMENTARY_DEMOGRAPHICS" = "select CUST_ID, EDUCATION, OCCUPATION, HOUSEHOLD_SIZE, YRS_RESIDENCE from SH.SUPPLEMENTARY_DEMOGRAPHICS"))
ore.sync(query = c("CUSTOMERS" = "select CUST_ID, CUST_GENDER, CUST_YEAR_OF_BIRTH, CUST_MARITAL_STATUS from SH.CUSTOMERS"))

CUST_DF <- merge(SUPPLEMENTARY_DEMOGRAPHICS,CUSTOMERS, by="CUST_ID")

  EMCS_NUM_EQUIWIDTH_BINS= 11,
  EMCS_REMOVE_COMPONENTS= 'EMCS_REMOVE_COMPS_ENABLE',

## Using SQL access prediction details
One feature of OML is the ability to use models from SQL as well as R. Prediction details are exposed through the R API and are available through the SQL API, which is illustrated here.

We first create a table from the R proxy object CUST_DF so that SQL can reference it. This could just as easily been a database view.
Then, since prediction details are provided as an XML string, we extract the elements to present them as table columns. The 'first attribute' identfies the feature and value that most influences the cluster assignment with corresponding weight. This is followed by the second and third attribute. In this example, we provide three, but additional attributes could be presented as well.

paragraphs.title: Create table for use in SQL query
List top 3 predictive attributes for specific customers with corresponding cluster assignments
paragraphs.text:
%sql

SELECT CUST_ID,
       CLUSTER_ID,
       ROUND(PROB*100,0) PROB_PCT,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute1",17,100)),'rank="1"/>') FIRST_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute2",17,100)),'rank="2"/>') SECOND_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute3",17,100)),'rank="3"/>') THIRD_ATTRIBUTE
FROM (SELECT CUST_ID, S.CLUSTER_ID, PROBABILITY PROB, 
             CLUSTER_DETAILS(EM_CLUSTERING_MODEL USING T.*) DETAIL
      FROM (SELECT V.*, CLUSTER_SET(EM_CLUSTERING_MODEL, NULL, 0.2 USING *) PSET
            FROM CUST_DF_EM V
            WHERE cust_id = ${CUST_ID ='100676','100676'|'101219'|'102805'}) T,
                  TABLE(T.PSET) S
            ORDER BY 2 DESC) OUT,
            XMLTABLE('/Details'
                      PASSING OUT.DETAIL
                      COLUMNS 
                      "Attribute1" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[1]',
                      "Attribute2" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[2]',
                      "Attribute3" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[3]') OUTPRED

SELECT CUST_ID,
       CLUSTER_ID,
       ROUND(PROB*100,0) PROB_PCT,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute1",17,100)),'rank="1"/>') FIRST_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute2",17,100)),'rank="2"/>') SECOND_ATTRIBUTE,
       RTRIM(TRIM(SUBSTR(OUTPRED."Attribute3",17,100)),'rank="3"/>') THIRD_ATTRIBUTE
FROM (SELECT CUST_ID, S.CLUSTER_ID, PROBABILITY PROB, 
             CLUSTER_DETAILS(EM_CLUSTERING_MODEL USING T.*) DETAIL
      FROM (SELECT V.*, CLUSTER_SET(EM_CLUSTERING_MODEL, NULL, 0.2 USING *) PSET
            FROM CUST_DF_EM V) T,
                  TABLE(T.PSET) S
            WHERE CUST_ID <= 100010
            ORDER BY 2 DESC) OUT,
            XMLTABLE('/Details'
                      PASSING OUT.DETAIL
                      COLUMNS 
                      "Attribute1" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[1]',
                      "Attribute2" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[2]',
                      "Attribute3" XMLType PATH 'Attribute[3]') OUTPRED
